{{Infobox person | name =Amy Wroe Bechtel | image = Amy_Wroe_Bechtel.jpg | image_size= 190px | caption = Portrait of Bechtel | birth_name = Amy Joy Wroe | birth_date = {{Birth date|1972|08|04}} | birth_place = [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], [[California]], U.S.<ref name=cbi>{{cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/amy_j_wroe_born_1972_11831254|work=[[California Birth Index]]|title=Amy J. Wroe|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> | disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|1997|07|24|1972|08|04}} | disappeared_place = [[Lander, Wyoming]], U.S. | disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1997|7|24}} | nationality = [[Americans|American]] | known_for = [[Missing person]] | alma_mater=[[University of Wyoming]] | height = {{convert|5|ft|6|in|cm|abbr=on}}<ref name=charley>{{cite web|url=http://www.charleyproject.org/cases/b/bechtel_amy.html|work=The Charley Project|title=Amy Joy Wroe Bechtel|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> | weight = {{convert|110|-|115|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=charley/> | parents = Duane and JoAnne Wroe{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=101}} | spouse = {{marriage|[[Steve Bechtel]]|1996}} }}
'''Amy Joy Wroe Bechtel''' (August 4, 1972<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/1838dfwy.html|title=The Doe Network: Case File 1838DFWY|website=www.doenetwork.org|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> – disappeared July 24, 1997;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/amy-joy-wroe-bechtel|title=Amy Joy Wroe Bechtel – The Charley Project|website=charleyproject.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> declared [[Declared death in absentia|legally dead]] 2004) is an [[Americans|American]] woman who [[list of people who disappeared mysteriously|disappeared]] while jogging in the [[Wind River Range|Wind River Mountains]] approximately {{convert|15|mi|km}} south of [[Lander, Wyoming|Lander]], [[Wyoming]]. Despite extensive investigative work and media portrayals, her case remains unsolved {{as of|2018|lc=y}}. She was declared dead in absentia by her husband, rock climber [[Steve Bechtel]], in 2004.
==Background== Bechtel was born Amy Joy Wroe in [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], [[California]] in 1972.<ref name=cbi/> She graduated from the [[University of Wyoming]], where she met her husband, [[Steve Bechtel]].<ref name=id>{{cite episode|series=[[Disappeared (TV series)|Disappeared]]|network=Investigation Discovery|airdate=January 7, 2013|title=Amy Wroe Bechtel}}</ref> In college, Bechtel was a competitive long distance runner, and hoped to try out for the [[2000 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=id/>{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=101}}
==Disappearance== On the morning of July 24, 1997, Bechtel told her husband, Steve, she was planning on running several errands in town after teaching a children's weight lifting class at the Wind River Fitness Center.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=102}} She stopped at Camera Connection, a photo store near her home in Lander, around 2:30pm after teaching her class.<ref name=charley/>{{Sfn|Scott|2009|p=103}} Following her time at the photo store, she stopped by Gallery 331, where she spoke to the proprietor, Greg Wagner.{{Sfn|Scott|2009|p=103}} Wagner noted that Bechtel seemed hurried, and repeatedly glanced at her watch during their conversation.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=103}} Wagner's was the last confirmed sighting of Bechtel.<ref name=charley/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/09/28/us/a-mystery-divides-family-in-wyoming.html|work=The [[New York Times]]|title=A Mystery Divides Family in Wyoming|date=September 28, 1997|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>
After leaving the photo shop, it is believed by authorities that Bechtel drove to the [[Shoshone National Forest]] to practice the course of an upcoming [[10K run]] she was enrolled to compete in.<ref name=id/> According to an eyewitness driving on Loop Road through the forest that afternoon, a woman resembling Bechtel was seen running along the road wearing black shorts similar to those she had worn earlier that day.<ref name=id/>
At 4:30pm, Steve returned home after having spent the day with a friend and found his wife absent.<ref name=id/> At 10:30pm, he called police to report his wife [[missing person|missing]].<ref name=id/> At 1:00am on the morning of July 25, Bechtel's car, a white [[Toyota Tercel]], was discovered parked on a turnout at Burnt Gulch in Lander.<ref name=lgg>{{cite web|url=http://www.runnersworld.com/runners-stories/long-gone-girl|work=[[Runner's World]]|title=Long Gone Girl|author=Billman, John|date=August 18, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=104}}
==Investigation== By 3:00am on July 25, 1997, an extensive search for Bechtel was underway from law enforcement, as well as Steve and the couple's friends and family.{{sfn|Scott|2009|pages=104–5}} By July 27, police were receiving roughly 1,000 calls per day with tips and potential leads in Bechtel's disappearance; additionally, various lakes and mines were searched with no results.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=105}}
Investigators initially believed Bechtel to have fallen victim to the elements or potentially been attacked by a [[bear]] or [[mountain lion]]; however, they later suspected Steve after uncovering a series of his journals describing violence towards women, and specifically, his wife.<ref name=id/> Detectives interrogated Steve on August 1, 1997, falsely claiming to have evidence proving he had murdered his wife; in response, Steve terminated the interview.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=108}} He would later claim the journals had comprised song lyrics he had written for his band, and that they were unrelated to Bechtel or her disappearance.<ref name=id/> In 1998, local police stated that Bechtel was not a central suspect in the case, but that they had wanted to clear him of suspicion in order to follow other leads, which they were unable to do after his lack of cooperation.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=109}} Steve provided an [[alibi]] for the time of Bechtel's disappearance, which was corroborated by friends who agreed they had spent the afternoon with him rock climbing.<ref name=lgg/> However, he refused to submit to a [[polygraph]] test.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=110}} Additionally, a woman driving through the area from where Bechtel disappeared claimed to have seen a truck matching Steve's in the area.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=110}}
In late August 1997, the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] requested satellite photos from [[NASA]] of the area on the day of Bechtel's disappearance, but the satellite images provided no information.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=112}} In January 1998, satellite images taken by the Russian space station ''[[Mir]]'' were also obtained by the FBI, but they also revealed nothing of note.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=114}}
===Later developments=== In June 2003, a [[Timex Group|Timex]] Iron Man [[Watch#Digital|digital watch]] was discovered by a doctor hiking near the Popo Agie River and was turned in to police. It was noted to be similar to a watch Bechtel had owned at the time of her disappearance; however, law enforcement was unable to determine whether or not the watch belonged to her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/possible-clue-found-to-woman-missing-6-years|work=The Denver Channel|title= Possible Clue Found To Woman Missing 6 Years|date=June 24, 2003|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>
In a 2007 interview with the ''[[Billings Gazette]]'', Sheriff Sgt. Roger Rizor stated: "I believe it was a [[homicide]], and I believe what happened to her happened on the day she disappeared. In my mind there is only one person that I want to talk to, only one person who has refused to talk to law enforcement, and that's her husband."<ref name=bg>{{cite web|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/wyoming/sheriff-believes-amy-wroe-bechtel-was-victim-of-killer/article_5c2b29d9-de5f-54b9-b0cb-a93aff383668.html|work=[[Billings Gazette]]|title=Sheriff believes Amy Wroe Bechtel was victim of killer|author=Tuttle, Greg|date=June 21, 2007|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>
[[Lil' Miss murder|Dale Wayne Eaton]], a convicted murderer on Wyoming's death row, has also been cited as a suspect in the case. According to Eaton's brother, he had been near the area where Bechtel disappeared at the time of her disappearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.county10.com/2013/03/05/amy-wroe-bechtel-disappearance-takes-new-turn-prime-suspect-on-wyomings-death-row/|work=County 10 |title=Amy Wroe Bechtel disappearance takes new turn; Prime suspect on Wyoming's Death Row|author=Over, Ernie|date=March 6, 2013|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> However, Eaton has refused to discuss the case.<ref name=charley/>
==Media depictions== Bechtel's case received significant media attention.<ref name=id/> On February 3, 1998, Steve appeared on ''[[Geraldo (TV series)|The Geraldo Rivera Show]]'' with Bechtel's sisters, who pleaded with him to provide information regarding her disappearance.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=115}}<ref name=cst>{{cite web|url=http://trib.com/news/state-and-regional/amy-wroe-bechtel-case-timeline/article_f289eca2-a639-5a75-a565-814f41b5249c.html|work=[[Casper Star Tribune]]|title=Amy Wroe Bechtel case timeline|date=July 22, 2007|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Steve denied any involvement in his wife's disappearance during the program.<ref name=id/>
The case was profiled in both ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine<ref>{{cite news|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|title=Into Thin Air|url=http://people.com/archive/into-thin-air-vol-49-no-11/|volume=49|number=11|author=Tresnowski, Alex|date=March 23, 1998|accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> and ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]'' in 1998,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1829016/long-gone|work=[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]|title=Long Gone|date=March 1, 1998|author1=Di Salvatore, Bryan|author2=McNamer, Deirdre|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> as well as the television series ''[[Unsolved Mysteries]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unsolved.com/gallery/amy-bechtel/|work=Unsolved.com|title=Amy Wroe Bechtel|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> It was later profiled on the series ''[[Disappeared (TV series)|Disappeared]]'' in 2013,<ref name=id/> and was also the subject of an extensive article featured in ''[[Runner's World]]'' in 2016.<ref name=lgg/>
